Having thus had occasion to introduce into the same note the names of my two friends, Mason and Delille, I cannot avoid adverting to the extraordinary coinci- dence of taste, time, and subject, which subsists be- tween their respective and exquisite didactic poems. The period in which they wrote was during the Ame- rican war: to this they both allude, and incline to the same side of politics. The subject of their poetry is Picturesque Gard‘ening: the title chosen by each is precisely similar. Their taste appears to have been formed from the same models, and directed to the same ends3 and they both speak in the most rap- turous terms of Poussin, Milton, and Kent.
